{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778191793,"nonce":"fxeDir3R8nYCalGcrXDLzWorv2w=","message":"**General hygiene principle for analyses — non-converged replicates must be excluded** (surfaced from `6fdf9a4` first induced-gain run, see prior coord comment).\n\nWhen an analysis pulls a single replicate from an ensemble (or a single seed from a multi-seed group), convergence of *that specific replicate* must be verified before its number is included. Train-time non-convergence on one replicate doesn't show up as an error at analysis time — it just produces garbage numbers that look superficially like real outputs. Without sibling comparison, the failure mode looks like \"this method just gives weird answers\" rather than \"replicate 0 of this method failed during training.\"\n\n**Live example from `6fdf9a4`:** `mult_single` replicate-0 produced γ_af = 15.6 vs ensemble-mate `mult_pop5` at γ_af = 0.18 — three orders of magnitude apart. The cross-method spread on every other group was within a factor 2 of each other, making the outlier obvious only by comparison. Filed as `4f2e934` for the specific spot-check.\n\n**Hygiene checks for any analysis going forward** (when in final/production mode, not exploratory):\n\n1. **Cross-replicate sanity.** Pull ≥ 2 replicates per group for the diagnostic pass even if the full analysis runs on one. Outlier filtering before reporting numbers.\n2. **Multi-seed spread reporting.** For methods with multiple seeds (e.g. minimax_single seeds 0–2), report median + spread; values \u003e ~10× from median are suspect.\n3. **Replicate index recorded in `run.json`.** Never silently substitute. If replicate 0 was excluded, log replicate 1 used + reason.\n4. **Outlier exclusion is a recorded decision, not silent smoothing.** Document in `notes.md` with the failure-mode hypothesis (e.g. \"replicate 0 didn't converge during warmup; ensemble-mate gives sensible value\") so the exclusion can be revisited if training is re-run.\n5. **Train-time convergence check** is the upstream fix. Eventually we should refuse to publish analyses on a non-converged checkpoint at all — but absent that, analysis-time outlier detection is the safety net.\n\n**Application to current state:** `6fdf9a4` first run is exploratory (single replicate per group, no convergence check); the cross-method table is exploratory until `4f2e934` resolves. When we revisit these analyses for the final phase, this comment is the reminder that *every* analysis needs the hygiene pass — not just the one that surfaced the issue.\n\n**Companion issues:** `4f2e934` (mult_single replicate-0 specific), `53b5fe5` (cycle-wires adapter fix surfaced from same run).","files":null}]}